Supervised Learning Classification Project: AllLife Bank Personal Loan Campaign¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

Data pre-processing¶

We've already shown that the data has no missing values and that there are no egregious outliers. An additional feature has been added to potentially be an important feature. We're ready for data modeling!

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

I am going to be using a Decision Tree Classifier for the following reasons:

  • We need a supervised model since we're trying to classify a target variable.
  • It works well with a categorical output (yes or no) and multiple types of input.
  • The results are intuitive to understand and the model is easy improve.

We will split the data into training and testing sets. A successful model will be able to correctly classify the 0s and 1s of the Personal Loan column given all the other features. There are two types of errors it can create:

  • Someone offered a personal loan who will refuse.
  • Someone not offered a personal loan who would accept.

There is little cost in offering a loan that falls through. The greater loss would be the missed opportunity for a potential customer that is not offered a loan. In essence, since false negatives are more costly, we prioritize recall as our performance metric (higher recall corresponds to fewer false negatives). We are not as worried about false positives.

Model Building¶

In [22]:
# X (input) is every feature except for the target variable
X = df.drop("Personal_Loan", axis=1).drop("ID", axis=1)
features = list(X.columns)

# y (output) is the target variable
y = df["Personal_Loan"]
In [23]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.3, random_state=1)
In [24]:
def DecisionTreeProcess(max_depth=None, ccp_alpha=0, verbose=True):
    #Create a decision tree with customizations and report the quickly relevant statistics.
    TREE = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini', max_depth=max_depth, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha, random_state=1)
    TREE.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    y_predict = TREE.predict(X_test)
    recall = metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_predict)
    
    if verbose:
        print(f"Accuracy on training set : {TREE.score(X_train, y_train):.1%}")
        print(f"Accuracy on test set : {TREE.score(X_test, y_test):.1%}")
        print(f"Recall on test set : {recall:.1%}")
    
    return TREE, y_predict
    
def make_confusion_matrix(model, y_actual , labels=[0, 1]):
    #Make a nice looking heatmap of the confusion matrix, showing the number of true/false positives/negatives.
    #Especially useful to see the rates of false positives and false negatives against each other.
    
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=labels)
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    
def getRecall(model):
    return metrics.recall_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test))

def getAccuracy(model):
    return metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test))

Overall, while 97.9% accuracy on the test set seems great, there is room for improvement. Firstly, our tree is too large. The final nodes of the tree only have a few samples each -- allowing a tree to run its full depth and have tiny mono-cultures is guaranteed to overfit your data. Futhermore, our recall score is 87.9%, which means we missed 12.1% of the customers that we might have had. Our model is perhaps too conservative. For the purposes of this problem, we don't mind sacrificing a little bit of accuracy to enhance our recall.

However, there is still much to learn from this. Before I try to adjust the model, I want to see which features were identified as the most impactful by the model.

In [28]:
importances = TREE.feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)

plt.title('Feature Importances')
plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color='violet', align='center')
plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [features[i] for i in indices])
plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')
plt.show()

Oh!

As I guessed, a simple correlation value was not sufficient for the two near-categorical features of Education and Family. This Decision Tree found that those were both top-3 features in determining class. On the other hand, the new category ExclusiveCC was not important at all.

This helps me to estimate how many nodes we might need for the optimized tree.

Model Performance Improvement¶

Pre-pruning¶

The feature importances chart showed that the top four features were Education, Income, Family, and CCAvg, in that order. We also know that Income and CCAvg are already highly correlated, so my initial guess is that the best max depth is going to be close to 3, but we can try a bunch of ranges.

In [29]:
#Try all depths between 1 and 10 (the original tree had 11)
depths = np.arange(1,11)

#For each value of depth, make a decision tree up to that depth and calculate its performance (recall)
recalls = []
trees = [""]  #This array will store the trees where trees[n] is the tree with a max depth n.
for d in depths:
    tr, y_p = DecisionTreeProcess(max_depth=d, verbose=False)
    trees.append(tr)
    recalls.append(metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_p))

#Plot the depths vs. recall performance
sns.scatterplot(x=depths, y=recalls)
plt.xlabel("Max Depth")
plt.ylabel("Recall")
plt.show()

The recall grows until we reach a max_depth of 4, and then it levels out. It is a little wobbly, and technically the highest recall is with a max_depth of 9, but I believe that's just noise due to the random selection of the training/testing data. Using a depth greater than 4 could just be hyperparameter overfitting.

While the tree is simpler, our recall went down as well. Adjusting max_depth didn't really result in a better model.

Post-pruning¶

Another method is to take the whole tree and cut off nodes that don't add value, instead of specifiying in advance how many nodes we want. We can accomplish this by varying the cost-complexity alpha values. Alpha can be thought of as a sliding scale of allowed impurity in a node, where alpha=0 means zero pruning. By slowly raising alpha and evaluating changes in the tree's performance, we might find an optimized value. We want to find the lowest alpha that still has good performance.

In [33]:
#The path shows the increasing alpha/impurity values we are willing to accept as we remove nodes.
path = TREE.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities

#This chart shows the increase in alpha/impurty for each node that we remove.
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
ax.plot(ccp_alphas[:-1], impurities[:-1], marker='o', drawstyle="steps-pre")
ax.set_xlabel("effective alpha")
ax.set_ylabel("total impurity of leaves")
ax.set_title("Total Impurity vs effective alpha for training set")
plt.show()

Alpha only needs to reach 0.06 before we've removed every node. This is because the full dataset is already kinda close to pure, with 91% of the data belonging to one class.

In [34]:
#For each alpha value, show the resulting decision tree and calculate its performance (recall/accuracy)
recalls = []
accuracies = []
trees = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas[:-1]:
    a_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
    a_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)    
    trees.append(a_tree)

recalls = [metrics.recall_score(y_test, a_tree.predict(X_test)) for a_tree in trees]
accuracies = [metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, a_tree.predict(X_test)) for a_tree in trees]

#Plot the recall/accuracy based on the alpha we're using.
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.set_xlabel("alpha")
ax.set_ylabel("accuracy")
ax.set_title("Accuracy and recall vs. alpha")
ax.plot(ccp_alphas[:-1], recalls, marker="o", label="recall", drawstyle="steps-post")
ax.plot(ccp_alphas[:-1], accuracies, marker="o", label="accuracy", drawstyle="steps-post")
ax.legend()
plt.show()

Let's pick the model with the highest recall.

I'm going to try applying KMeans clustering to our original dataframe without designating Personal_Loan as a target variable. It may work out that certain clusters have higher personal loan rates and give more insight into the attributes that people who accept personal loans might have.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters=range(2,15)

sils = []
dists = []

#Attempt KMeans clustering with different numbers of clusters, from 1 to 15.
#We will store the silhouette scores and average to-cluster-center-distances for each model.
for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(kdf)
    labels = model.labels_
    sils.append(silhouette_score(kdf, labels, metric='euclidean'))
    dists.append(sum(np.min(cdist(kdf, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / kdf.shape[0])
In [42]:
sns.lineplot(x=clusters, y=dists, marker='o')
plt.xlabel("Clusters")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
Out[42]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Average Distortion')

The distortion is the Euclidian distance from a point to its cluster's center. The average distortion goes down with more clusters because you can capture tighter groups if you need fewer points per group. The "elbow method" is one way to determine the best number of clusters to use by visually determining at which point adding more clusters doesn't decrease distortions as much. This graph is difficult to parse out, though. Perhaps there's a kink in the line at 10 clusters?

My initial reaction is that 10 would be good because we know that about 9%, or sorta close to 1-in-10, accepted the personal loan. We need about that level of resolution for the clusters to be sensitive to personal loan acceptance. However, with more ambiguous cases such as this, there is also a more mathematical way to determine it. The silhouette score is a comparison of the distances of each point within a cluster vs. the distances of each cluster. Higher silhouette scores correspond to more "natural" clustering, and it's reasonable to choose the number k that maximizes this score.

In [43]:
sns.lineplot(x=clusters, y=sils, marker='o')

In this case (excluding 2-4 clusters, which probably isn't large enough for as many features as we have), we actually have a good case of choosing 10 as our cluster number.

First, if we look at the Personal Loan rates, we see some interesting trends, though perhaps more interesting than useful.

There are three groups (4, 5, and 6) that have much higher personal loan rates than the others, up to 42% of Group 5! If we look through the other columns, we see that those three groups all have significantly higher values for Income, CD_Account, and CCAvg.

It's hard to tell how much we can really learn from this. The "base rate" of acceptance is 9%, so it feels meaningful that you can designate a group that has an acceptance rate of 42% instead. However, this also feels like a convoluted and inferior way to arrive at some of the same conclusions that we found in our Decision Tree, which had much higher accuracy/recall than 42%. We can look at the visualization of the Decision Tree and see that there are 17 nodes that are "terminal", which are arrived at by comparing several features against thresholds, and in one sense we can kind of consider these 17 terminal nodes to be clusters of their own.

The highest performing model is the Decision Tree with the optimized alpha value, from post-pruning. We can choose this tree to look at which features are the most important.

In order to identify the customers we're looking for (class 1), you can look at each line where this text decision tree gives ends by assigning class 1, but also by looking at the weights. For example, the final row of this tree says "weights: [0.00, 222.00] class: 1". This indicates that the process found a cluster of 222 people with 100% acceptance rate. What do they have in common? We know their Income > $116.50k and their Education is graduate or better. All 22 people who follow those two rules accepted the loan. This one line is why the Feature Importances chart showed that Education is the single most impactful feature.

Continuing this method, let's look at the line above: "weights: [0.00, 47.00] class: 1". This is another pure group of 47 customers with 100% acceptance. They have high income (greater than $116.50k), only undergraduate education, but larger families (3+). Perhaps the addition of children makes those with high income and low education feel more pressure or need for a loan.

The other biggest chunks are the ones with very low acceptance rates. One of the first lines is "weights: [2553.00, 0.00] class: 0". This is a whopping 2553 people from whom no one accepted a personal loan. The features that define this cluster are "lower" income (less than 106.50k dollars) and low credit card spending (less than $2950/month).

Looking at the rest of them, most of these nodes are pretty small. There are 5 people with low income, high cc spending, higher age, and a small family that all accepted loans. But 9 customers with the same attributes except for having larger families instead rejected personal loans.

I said earlier that the cost of offering a loan is low, and that statement requires review. If I am an agent of the bank, and I have 10 meetings in a day with potential customers, and I only close on one loan, is that a success? It would take me 500 days or 100 agents 5 days to go through 5000 customers and would only close on (from this dataset) 480 loans.

If, however, we followed this decision tree and set up 145 meetings, and closed on 138 of them, that would be an incredible boost to efficiency. That is something I could do as a single agent in about two business weeks. In this case we would only be missing out on 7 potential customers as well.

My initial instinct that we should cast a wide net might be incorrect. For this reason, with everything being taken into account, I believe it's in the best interest of the bank to follow the decision tree model set out here and offer loans to those classified by the model to likely accept them.
